  "text": "To identify the protective mechanisms regulated by MyD88-signaling in B cells during this rechallenge experiment, we infected vaccinated mice with attenuated Salmonella (SL7207) and analyzed innate and adaptive immune responses 5 days later, when bacterial loads were similar in spleens and livers of B-WT and B-Myd88 À/À mice ( Figure S5A ). Because the protection afforded by the attenuated Salmonella vaccine involves antibody production [CITATION_1] , we measured amounts of Salmonella-reactive antibodies in serum of vaccinated mice before and after rechallenge. Serum antibody titers were comparable at day 90 in vaccinated B-WT and B-Myd88 À/À mice, and they were not significantly modulated at day 5 after reinfection ( Figure S5B ). We then examined whether MyD88 signaling in B cells influenced memory T cell responses occurring in spleen and BM [CITATION_2] . Salmonella-reactive IFN-g-, TNF-a-, and IL-10-producing CD4 + and CD8 + T cells were present in equal numbers in spleen and BM of B-WT and B-Myd88 À/À mice at day 90 postvaccination (Figures 7B and 7C ; Figure S6C ). Anamnestic T cell responses were also similar at day 5 after rechallenge in B-WT and B-Myd88 À/À mice, as shown by analyzes of production of IFN-g, TNF-a, or IL-10 by CD4 + and CD8 + T cells from spleen and BM (Figures 7B and 7C ; Figure S6C ). T cell responses were not detected at day 5 p.i. in naive mice (data not shown). Thus, MyD88 signaling in B cells does not appear to modulate the formation or the reactivation of memory T cells at the time points analyzed. This is consistent with our observations in naive chimera mice, in which differences in T cell responses were only observed between B-WT and B-Myd88 À/À mice at day 21 p.i. (Figures 4A-4C) .",
